### Method Overloading

Method overloading is when a class has multiple definitions of the same method name but with **different parameters** (type, number, or order). For example: `print(int num)` and `print(String str)`. Overloading does **not require inheritance**, although you can overload inherited methods. The parameters **must be different**, and the return type can be the same or different, but it **cannot be the only difference**. The method to be used is decided at **compile time**, based on the arguments passed, which is called **static binding**.

---

### Method Overriding

Method overriding is when a child class provides a new implementation of a method inherited from a superclass. The method must have the **same name and parameters (same signature)**, and the return type must be the same or a **covariant type** (a subclass of the original return type). Overriding **requires inheritance**, unlike overloading. At compile time, the method call is checked using the reference type, but the actual method that gets executed is determined at **runtime** based on the object instance. This is called **dynamic binding**.

